            @* ----- Content ----- *@
            <article class="max-w-3xl">
                <p class="text-[10px] font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-dgb-500 mb-2">WooCommerce install guide · v0.1.0</p>
                <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 slide-up">Accept DigiByte in WooCommerce</h1>
                <p class="text-base sm:text-lg text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed mb-8 slide-up-delay-1">
                    A drop-in WordPress plugin that adds DigiByte (DGB) as a payment option at WooCommerce checkout.
                    Hosted-checkout flow, HMAC-signed webhooks with replay protection, fiat-priced orders converted
                    to DGB at the live rate, and an auto-redirect back to your thank-you page once payment confirms.
                    Non-custodial — payments land directly in your wallet. ~10 minutes from "I want to accept DGB"
                    to a verified test order.
                </p>

                @* ---------- Before you start ---------- *@
                <section id="before" class="scroll-mt-20 mb-12">
                    <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Before you start</h2>
                    <ul class="space-y-2 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 list-disc pl-5 mb-4">
                        <li>A WooCommerce store running on WordPress 6.0+, WooCommerce 7.0+, PHP 7.4+.</li>
                        <li>Your store's public URL — the webhook needs to be reachable from DigiPay's network. Use <a href="https://ngrok.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-dgb-500 hover:underline">ngrok</a> or similar for local testing.</li>
                        <li>A DigiByte address or BIP84 xpub where DGB payments will land. If you don't have one, install <a href="https://dgbwallet.app" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-dgb-500 hover:underline">DigiByte Wallet</a> first.</li>
                        <li>Outbound HTTPS — the plugin fetches DGB prices from CoinGecko for fiat-priced orders.</li>
                    </ul>
                </section>

                @* ---------- 1. Get the ZIP ---------- *@
                <section id="zip" class="scroll-mt-20 mb-12">
                    <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">1. Get the plugin ZIP</h2>
                    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 mb-3">
                        Download <code class="font-mono text-xs px-1 py-0.5 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 rounded">digipay-for-woocommerce-0.1.0.zip</code>
                        from the <a href="https://github.com/DennisPitallano/digibyte-wallet/releases" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-dgb-500 hover:underline">GitHub releases</a> page.
                        Building from source is also fine — clone the repo and run the bundled <code class="font-mono text-xs px-1 py-0.5 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 rounded">scripts/build-woocommerce-zip.sh</code>.
                    </p>
                </section>

                @* ---------- 2. Upload + activate ---------- *@
                <section id="upload" class="scroll-mt-20 mb-12">
                    <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">2. Upload + activate the plugin</h2>
                    <ol class="space-y-2 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 list-decimal pl-5 mb-4">
                        <li>In WordPress admin go to <strong>Plugins → Add New → Upload Plugin</strong>.</li>
                        <li>Choose the ZIP and click <strong>Install Now</strong>.</li>
                        <li>Click <strong>Activate Plugin</strong>.</li>
                    </ol>
                    <figure class="mb-5 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 shadow-sm">
                        <img src="@($"/img/woocommerce/01-install-upload.png{ImgV}")"
                             alt="WordPress admin Plugins page with Upload Plugin selected"
                             loading="lazy" class="block w-full h-auto" />
                        <figcaption class="px-4 py-2 text-xs text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 border-t border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800">
                            WP admin — Plugins → Add New → Upload Plugin.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <div class="p-3 bg-slate-100 dark:bg-dgb-900/40 border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 rounded-xl text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
                        The plugin loads but the gateway is automatically <strong>hidden at checkout</strong> until step 4 — no half-configured "broken" state for buyers to stumble into.
                    </div>
                </section>

                @* ---------- 3. Register a DigiPay merchant ---------- *@
                <section id="account" class="scroll-mt-20 mb-12">
                    <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">3. Register a DigiPay merchant account</h2>
                    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 mb-3">
                        The plugin talks to a DigiPay backend, so you need an account there too. Two paths:
                    </p>

                    <h3 class="text-base font-bold mt-4 mb-2 tracking-tight">Hosted DigiPay (recommended)</h3>
                    <ol class="space-y-2 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 list-decimal pl-5 mb-4">
                        <li><a href="/merchant/signin" class="text-dgb-500 hover:underline">Sign in</a> here on <code class="font-mono text-xs px-1 py-0.5 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 rounded">pay.dgbwallet.app</code> via Digi-ID — passwordless, sign in with any DigiByte wallet.</li>
                        <li>Create a <strong>store</strong> with your DigiByte address (or xpub for per-session derivation — recommended for buyer privacy).</li>
                        <li>Under <strong>API keys</strong>, click <strong>Create</strong>. Copy the key — it starts with <code class="font-mono text-xs px-1 py-0.5 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 rounded">dgp_…</code> and is shown only once.</li>
                        <li>Under <strong>Webhook</strong>, paste your store's webhook URL. The plugin's settings page shows the exact URL — it looks like <code class="font-mono text-xs px-1 py-0.5 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 rounded">https://yourshop.example/?wc-api=digipay_webhook</code>. Save and copy the generated webhook secret.</li>
                    </ol>

                    <h3 class="text-base font-bold mt-4 mb-2 tracking-tight">Self-hosted DigiPay</h3>
                    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 mb-3">
                        Same flow against your own deployment. In step 4, set the plugin's <strong>API base URL</strong> to your self-hosted Pay.Api endpoint instead of the default.
                    </p>
                </section>

                @* ---------- 4. Configure the plugin ---------- *@
                <section id="configure" class="scroll-mt-20 mb-12">
                    <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">4. Configure the plugin</h2>
                    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 mb-3">
                        Go to <strong>WooCommerce → Settings → Payments → DigiPay (DigiByte)</strong>. Paste in the API key and webhook secret from step 3, tick <em>Enable DigiPay (DigiByte)</em>, save.
                    </p>
                    <figure class="mb-5 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 shadow-sm">
                        <img src="@($"/img/woocommerce/02-settings.png{ImgV}")"
                             alt="DigiPay plugin settings page in WooCommerce admin with API key and webhook secret fields"
                             loading="lazy" class="block w-full h-auto" />
                        <figcaption class="px-4 py-2 text-xs text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 border-t border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800">
                            DigiPay plugin settings. The webhook URL to register on the dashboard side is shown verbatim — no guessing.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 mb-3">
                        <table class="w-full text-sm">
                            <thead>
                                <tr class="text-left text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 border-b border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 bg-slate-50 dark:bg-dgb-900/50">
                                    <th class="py-3 px-4 font-semibold">Setting</th>
                                    <th class="py-3 px-4 font-semibold">What to choose</th>
                                </tr>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody class="[&_td]:py-2.5 [&_td]:px-4 [&_tr:not(:last-child)_td]:border-b [&_tr:not(:last-child)_td]:border-slate-100 dark:[&_tr:not(:last-child)_td]:border-dgb-800/60 align-top">
                                <tr><td class="font-semibold">Title</td><td>What buyers see at checkout. Default <em>DigiByte (DGB)</em>.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td class="font-semibold">Description</td><td>One-line explainer under the title at checkout.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td class="font-semibold">API base URL</td><td>Default <code class="font-mono text-xs">https://pay.dgbwallet.app</code>. Override for self-hosted.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td class="font-semibold">API key</td><td>The <code class="font-mono text-xs">dgp_…</code> key from step 3.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td class="font-semibold">Webhook secret</td><td>From DigiPay dashboard → Webhook.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td class="font-semibold">Currency mode</td><td><strong>Fiat</strong> (recommended) if your store is priced in USD/EUR/GBP/PHP/JPY — DigiPay converts at the live rate. <strong>DGB</strong> if your store currency is DigiByte itself.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td class="font-semibold">Session expiry</td><td>Leave blank for the DigiPay default (1800s / 30 min).</td></tr>
                                <tr><td class="font-semibold">Debug logging</td><td>On while setting up; off in production. Logs to <em>WooCommerce → Status → Logs → digipay</em>.</td></tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>
                </section>

                @* ---------- 5. Verify at checkout ---------- *@
                <section id="verify" class="scroll-mt-20 mb-12">
                    <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">5. Verify the gateway shows at checkout</h2>
                    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 mb-3">
                        Add any product to your cart and go to checkout. Under <em>Payment options</em> you should see <strong>DigiByte (DGB)</strong> with the official DigiByte coin mark.
                    </p>
                    <figure class="mb-5 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 shadow-sm">
                        <img src="@($"/img/woocommerce/03-checkout-radio.png{ImgV}")"
                             alt="WooCommerce block-based checkout showing DigiByte (DGB) as a payment option"
                             loading="lazy" class="block w-full h-auto" />
                        <figcaption class="px-4 py-2 text-xs text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 border-t border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800">
                            Block-based WC checkout — DigiByte (DGB) selected.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <div class="p-3 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800/50 rounded-xl text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-200">
                        <strong>Missing?</strong> The plugin auto-hides itself when the API key, webhook secret, or a supported store currency is missing. Re-check the settings page — the gateway will reappear once everything's filled in.
                    </div>
                </section>

                @* ---------- 6. Place a test order ---------- *@
                <section id="test" class="scroll-mt-20 mb-12">
                    <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">6. Place a test order</h2>
                    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 mb-3">
                        Click <strong>Place Order</strong>. The plugin posts to DigiPay's API (with an idempotency key derived from the WC order id, so a double-clicked Place Order can never create two invoices) and redirects you to the hosted checkout:
                    </p>
                    <figure class="mb-5 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 shadow-sm">
                        <img src="@($"/img/woocommerce/04-hosted-checkout-qr.png{ImgV}")"
                             alt="DigiPay hosted checkout page showing a QR code, the receive address, and an expiry countdown"
                             loading="lazy" class="block w-full h-auto" />
                        <figcaption class="px-4 py-2 text-xs text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 border-t border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800">
                            Hosted checkout — fresh-derived BIP84 address, QR, and a 30-min price-locked countdown.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 mb-3">
                        Pay the invoice from any DigiByte wallet you control. Once the chain confirms, the page flips to:
                    </p>
                    <figure class="mb-5 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 shadow-sm">
                        <img src="@($"/img/woocommerce/05-payment-confirmed.png{ImgV}")"
                             alt="Payment confirmed state with Return to merchant button and 5-second auto-redirect countdown"
                             loading="lazy" class="block w-full h-auto" />
                        <figcaption class="px-4 py-2 text-xs text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 border-t border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800">
                            Confirmed — <strong>Return to merchant</strong> button + 5-second auto-redirect.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 mb-3">
                        The buyer's browser auto-redirects (or they click) back to your WC thank-you page:
                    </p>
                    <figure class="mb-5 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 shadow-sm">
                        <img src="@($"/img/woocommerce/06-thankyou.png{ImgV}")"
                             alt="WooCommerce thank-you page showing order completed"
                             loading="lazy" class="block w-full h-auto" />
                        <figcaption class="px-4 py-2 text-xs text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 border-t border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800">
                            WooCommerce thank-you page (<code class="font-mono text-xs">/checkout/order-received/{id}/?key=…</code>).
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                </section>

                @* ---------- 7. Confirm in WC admin ---------- *@
                <section id="confirm" class="scroll-mt-20 mb-12">
                    <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">7. Confirm the order completed</h2>
                    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 mb-3">
                        In WP admin go to <strong>WooCommerce → Orders</strong> and open your test order:
                    </p>
                    <figure class="mb-5 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800 bg-white dark:bg-dgb-900 shadow-sm">
                        <img src="@($"/img/woocommerce/07-wc-order-admin.png{ImgV}")"
                             alt="WooCommerce order admin showing Completed status, payment via DigiByte (DGB), and the txid"
                             loading="lazy" class="block w-full h-auto" />
                        <figcaption class="px-4 py-2 text-xs text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 border-t border-slate-200 dark:border-dgb-800">
                            WC order admin — <em>Completed</em>, payment via DigiByte (DGB), txid recorded.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 mb-3">You should see:</p>
                    <ul class="space-y-1 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 list-disc pl-5">
                        <li>Status: <strong>Completed</strong> (or <em>Processing</em> while waiting on confirmations)</li>
                        <li>The DigiByte txid recorded as the order's payment transaction id</li>
                        <li><em>Payment via DigiByte (DGB)</em> with the txid in the order header</li>
                        <li>Order notes containing the DigiPay session id and webhook events as they fire</li>
                    </ul>
                </section>

                @* ---------- Troubleshooting ---------- *@
                <section id="troubleshoot" class="scroll-mt-20 mb-12">
                    <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Troubleshooting</h2>
                    <div class="space-y-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
                        <div>
                            <p class="font-semibold mb-1">DigiByte doesn't show as a payment option at checkout.</p>
                            <p class="text-sm m-0">Most likely the API key, webhook secret, or store currency is missing. The plugin auto-hides itself in those cases. Open <em>WC → Settings → Payments → DigiPay</em> and confirm all required fields are filled in.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <p class="font-semibold mb-1">"Could not start a DigiPay payment: amount (DGB) must be > 0".</p>
                            <p class="text-sm m-0">The plugin couldn't fetch the DGB price from CoinGecko. Confirm outbound HTTPS is allowed from your WordPress host, and that your store currency is one of <strong>USD, EUR, GBP, PHP, JPY</strong>. Switch to <em>DGB</em> currency mode if your store is priced in DigiByte itself.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Order stays in <em>Pending payment</em> after the buyer paid.</p>
                            <p class="text-sm m-0">The webhook isn't reaching your store. Check the <em>DigiPay dashboard → Stores → Webhook deliveries</em> log for the response code. Localhost webhook URLs only work in dev — production needs a publicly reachable URL.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Webhook delivered but order status didn't change.</p>
                            <p class="text-sm m-0">Turn on <em>Debug logging</em> in the plugin settings and tail <em>WooCommerce → Status → Logs → digipay-…</em>. The most common cause is a webhook secret mismatch (HMAC verification fails with 401) or a stale-replay rejection (delivery timestamp older than 5 min).</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

